1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,780
Imagine you're working on a puzzle where each piece is interconnected and solving

2

00:00:04,780  -->  00:00:10,420
one piece helps you get closer to solving the next part of the puzzle and so on.

3

00:00:10,420  -->  00:00:13,380
Recursion in Python work similarly to this.

4

00:00:13,380  -->  00:00:16,000
It's a technique where a function calls itself,

5

00:00:16,000  -->  00:00:19,680
allowing you to break down complex problems into smaller,

6

00:00:19,680  -->  00:00:22,265
more manageable steps automatically.

7

00:00:22,265  -->  00:00:24,650
Let's say you have a mountain of books that need

8

00:00:24,650  -->  00:00:27,950
sorting one by one into an ordered stack.

9

00:00:27,950  -->  00:00:30,670
Instead of tackling the entire pile at once,

10

00:00:30,670  -->  00:00:32,090
you pick up one book,

11

00:00:32,090  -->  00:00:36,450
organize it, then hand the rest of the pile back to yourself to continue sorting.

12

00:00:36,450  -->  00:00:40,730
This process repeats until there are no more books left to sort.

13

00:00:40,730  -->  00:00:46,570
In Python, recursion can help you with tasks that involve repetitive patterns or steps,

14

00:00:46,570  -->  00:00:49,130
especially when the problem can be broken down

15

00:00:49,130  -->  00:00:52,210
into smaller sub problems of the same kind.

16

00:00:52,210  -->  00:00:54,175
So when should we use recursion?

17

00:00:54,175  -->  00:00:58,200
Recursion is particularly useful in compartmentalization,

18

00:00:58,200  -->  00:01:00,160
where the problem can be divided into

19

00:01:00,160  -->  00:01:03,535
smaller sub problems that mirror the larger problem.

20

00:01:03,535  -->  00:01:07,500
In simplification, when you want to simplify code that

21

00:01:07,500  -->  00:01:12,420
involves repeated tasks by letting each task built on the previous one,

22

00:01:12,420  -->  00:01:14,540
and in mathematical operations,

23

00:01:14,540  -->  00:01:17,960
where you are tackling problems like tree traversal,

24

00:01:17,960  -->  00:01:21,980
sequence generation, or mathematical operations such as factorials,

25

00:01:21,980  -->  00:01:25,360
that naturally lend themselves to recursive solutions.

26

00:01:25,360  -->  00:01:27,765
When shouldn't we use recursion?

27

00:01:27,765  -->  00:01:31,410
Recursion can be inefficient or problematic when there are

28

00:01:31,410  -->  00:01:36,890
memory constraints because each recursive call adds a new layer to the call stack,

29

00:01:36,890  -->  00:01:40,610
which can quickly exhaust memory and lead to stack overflow errors,

30

00:01:40,610  -->  00:01:43,250
especially for deep or infinite recursions.

31

00:01:43,250  -->  00:01:46,970
Performance concerns, as recursion can be slower than

32

00:01:46,970  -->  00:01:51,010
iterative approaches due to the overhead of multiple function calls,

33

00:01:51,010  -->  00:01:55,570
particularly for tasks that require a large number of iterations.

34

00:01:55,570  -->  00:01:58,025
Or there is great complexity.

35

00:01:58,025  -->  00:02:02,480
Such as if the problem doesn't inherently break down into smaller sub problems,

36

00:02:02,480  -->  00:02:06,260
recursion might add unnecessary complexity to your code.

37

00:02:06,260  -->  00:02:11,390
Let's see some examples where we see recursion in action to add more clarity.

38

00:02:11,390  -->  00:02:14,790
In this demo, we're going to be talking about recursion.

39

00:02:14,790  -->  00:02:20,390
Let's see an example of recursion in action by calculating the factorial of a number.

40

00:02:20,390  -->  00:02:24,810
The factorial of a number n written as n with

41

00:02:24,810  -->  00:02:31,190
an exclamation point is the product of all positive integers leading up to that number.

42

00:02:31,190  -->  00:02:34,070
The factorial of a number will look like that.

43

00:02:34,070  -->  00:02:40,100
For example, five factorial is really this.

44

00:02:40,350  -->  00:02:47,960
It's 5*4*3*2*1 which equals 120,

45

00:02:47,960  -->  00:02:53,840
and we can make sure that this is true because if we do this,

46

00:02:53,840  -->  00:02:59,720
we'll change these xs to asterisks to indicate times.

47

00:02:59,720  -->  00:03:07,900
What can say is five factorial equals this times this times this,

48

00:03:07,900  -->  00:03:11,400
and then we can print the value of this.

49

00:03:12,430  -->  00:03:15,190
We'll see that this is in fact,

50

00:03:15,190  -->  00:03:19,030
120 or five factorial equals 120.

51

00:03:19,030  -->  00:03:24,450
But imagine if we wanted to get the factorial of 100 or 1,000 or 10,000.

52

00:03:24,450  -->  00:03:27,010
This would be way too much work to do by hand,

53

00:03:27,010  -->  00:03:29,830
so we'll want to leverage recursion in Python to help

54

00:03:29,830  -->  00:03:33,175
automate this process for us. How would we do this?

55

00:03:33,175  -->  00:03:36,480
First, we'll define the function of factorial

56

00:03:36,480  -->  00:03:40,200
n where n is the number we want to calculate the factorial of.

57

00:03:40,200  -->  00:03:43,340
Next, we'll set up the base case to stop the recursion.

58

00:03:43,340  -->  00:03:48,180
If n is one, we return a one because the factorial of one is itself.

59

00:03:48,180  -->  00:03:50,520
This is how we will prevent infinite recursion,

60

00:03:50,520  -->  00:03:54,180
which is a type of infinite loop like we learned about earlier in the course.

61

00:03:54,180  -->  00:03:57,680
We need to escape the function from running forever.

62

00:03:57,680  -->  00:04:01,030
This is how we'll do that. For n values greater than one,

63

00:04:01,030  -->  00:04:05,970
we multiply n by the result of factorial n minus one.

64

00:04:05,970  -->  00:04:09,230
This pattern repeats until n equals one.

65

00:04:09,230  -->  00:04:10,730
When the base case is met,

66

00:04:10,730  -->  00:04:14,130
which will stop the recursion loop from continuing.

67

00:04:14,130  -->  00:04:16,810
When the base case is reached,

68

00:04:16,810  -->  00:04:21,510
our function begins to return results back up the chain of calls,

69

00:04:21,510  -->  00:04:23,730
multiplying each returned value by n,

70

00:04:23,730  -->  00:04:27,510
and this is how the full factorial is calculated with Python.

71

00:04:27,510  -->  00:04:30,570
Let's write a function to illustrate this.

72

00:04:30,570  -->  00:04:36,220
We'll write def factorial and we'll put n for the placeholder of the input.

73

00:04:36,220  -->  00:04:39,640
Then we'll say if n equals equals one,

74

00:04:39,640  -->  00:04:44,640
then return one, and this is to prevent our infinite loop like we talked about before.

75

00:04:44,640  -->  00:04:48,180
Otherwise, we'll continue with our recursive loop,

76

00:04:48,180  -->  00:04:51,880
and we'll say, else, colon return.

77

00:04:52,520  -->  00:04:58,840
N times factorial n minus one.

78

00:04:58,840  -->  00:05:01,860
We'll save this function to our Jupiter notebook,

79

00:05:01,860  -->  00:05:04,320
and will this actually work?

80

00:05:04,320  -->  00:05:06,280
Well, let's test it out and find out.

81

00:05:06,280  -->  00:05:09,180
If we were to print the factorial,

82

00:05:09,180  -->  00:05:10,880
which we copy from here,

83

00:05:10,880  -->  00:05:13,560
and we put in five into our input.

84

00:05:13,560  -->  00:05:17,985
Can you guess what the output is going to be when we run our function?

85

00:05:17,985  -->  00:05:20,260
It prints out 120,

86

00:05:20,260  -->  00:05:24,740
which means that our factorial function worked.

87

00:05:24,740  -->  00:05:28,180
Recursion is a powerful tool for solving

88

00:05:28,180  -->  00:05:33,040
complex problems by breaking them into manageable steps just like this.

89

00:05:33,040  -->  00:05:37,020
Remember to always define a base case to prevent infinite loops and be

90

00:05:37,020  -->  00:05:41,800
mindful of memory usage when dealing with deep recursion. Great job.
